The conditions for determination of ClO− by NIR-CDs were optimized (provided by supplementary material), including reaction time, temperature and pH. Fig. 5
                        A shows the emission intensity of NIR-CDs (15 μg·mL−1) at 653 nm decreases regularly with the addition of ClO− concentration (0–25 μM) gradually increased. The inset in Fig. 5A shows NIR-CDs solution (15 μg·mL−1) emit a bright NIR fluorescence, and the fluorescence intensity is significantly quenched when ClO− (25 μM) is added. Meanwhile, the value of F/F0 presents a good linear relationship toward ClO− concentration of 2–12 μM (R2 = 0.9900), and F0 and F are the emission intensities of NIR-CDs at 653 nm before and after the addition of ClO−, respectively (Fig. 5B). With the signal-to-noise of 3, the estimated limit of detection (LOD) for ClO− is 42.7 nM, indicating that NIR-CDs have excellent sensitivity to ClO−. Moreover, we compared the performance of previously reported CD-based ClO− probes with that of the NIR-CDs in detail (Table 1
                        ). The NIR-CDs prepared in this work have advantages over most reported CDs materials in terms of emission wavelength and sensitivity. Moreover, the respond time of NIR-CDs to ClO− is comparable to these reports.
